var title_f15_24_15744="MR in atrial fibrillation as heard at the apex";
var content_f15_24_15744=[" <div id=\"graphicsToolbar\">",
"  <div id=\"graphicsCopy\">",
"   &copy;2013 UpToDate",
"   <sup>",
"    &reg;",
"   </sup>",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"graphicsLinks\">",
"   <a class=\"etacLink\" href=\"#\">",
"    <img alt=\"Email graphic(s)\" src=\"./../images/icn_email.myextg\" title=\"Email graphic(s)\"/>",
"   </a>",
"   <a class=\"icontxt textLink etacLink\" href=\"#\" title=\"Email graphic(s)\">",
"    Email",
"   </a>",
"  </div>",
" </div>",
" <div class=\"graphic2\" style=\"width: 1102px;\">",
"  <div class=\"videoplayer\" h264=\"./images/CARD/56783/mrafapex_conv.mp4?title=MR+in+atrial+fibrillation+as+heard+at+the+apex\" style=\"width:512px;height:458px\">",
"  </div>",
"  <div class=\"figure\" style=\"width: 470px\">",
"   <div class=\"ttl\">",
"    Mitral regurgitation in atrial fibrillation as heard at the apex",
"   </div>",
"   <div class=\"cntnt\" style=\"width: 444px; height: 232px; background-image: url(data:image/jpeg;base64,);\">",
"   </div>",
"   <div class=\"lgnd\">",
"    Electrocardiogram and phonocardiogram of mitral regurgitation as heard at the apex. After S1 (closure of mitral and tricuspid valves) there is a harsh, holosystolic murmur of mitral regurgitation. Following S2 (closure of the aortic and pulmonic valves) there is a third heart sound (S3) which results from rapid filling of a dilated left ventricle. An early diastolic murmur is due to the large volume of blood flow from the left atrium into left ventricle, a result of mitral regurgitation.",
"    <div class=\"footnotes\">",
"    </div>",
"    <div class=\"reference\">",
"     Provided by John M Criley, MD, The Physiological Origins of Heart Sounds and Murmurs, Little, Brown, Boston, 1996, 1-800-527-0145. This program contains a complete interactive tutorial integrating over 200 heart sounds and murmurs with cineangiographic, echo-Doppler, and hemodynamic motion picture sequences.",
"    </div>",
"   </div>",
"  </div>",
" </div>",
"</div>"].join("\n");
